ce:section.ce:para:
Ti recoveries in the grain refiner alloys produced with the conventional halide salt process (Table 1
) are lower than those obtained in another set, produced in the same manner except for the holding step which was employed in a resistance furnace with the spent salt on the melt until before casting [9]. The oxidation of the molten alloy during holding without the protection provided by the molten salt cover is thus claimed to be responsible for the lower Ti recoveries in the former. This is evidenced by the marked improvement noted in the Ti recovery by simply moving the decanting operation to the end of the production cycle (Table 2
).

Of the several alloys produced by employing different holding temperatures, alloy 2, produced at a holding temperature of 800°C, appears to produce the smallest grains for the entire range of contact times, with an average grain size 2min after inoculation of 135μm (Fig. 3
). While judged to be also well within the acceptance range, the grain sizes of samples inoculated with alloy 1, for which the holding temperature was 750°C, are running slightly higher. The grain refinement provided by alloys 3 and 4, produced by holding the molten alloy at 850°C and 900°C, respectively, are relatively inferior. The smallest grain size achieved after inoculation with the latter two alloys was 207μm. When rating the performance of the experimental alloys with respect to holding time (alloys 2, 5 and 6), alloy 2, the holding treatment at 800°C of which lasted 30min, was once again found to exhibit the best grain refining efficiency (Fig. 4
). The inferior performance of alloy 5, held at 800°C for only 10min, is linked with the time it takes for the salt reaction to reach completion. Ti yield increases continuously with holding time after salt addition and a minimum of 15min is required for the Ti recovery to reach acceptable levels (Fig. 5
). This is taken to imply that the salt reaction lasts at least 15min. The effect of holding time on the grain refinement performance is quite similar to that of holding temperature, prolonged holding degrading the performance.

The above account which holds the Ti content responsible for the variations in the grain refinement performances is a plausible yet an incomplete one. This is evidenced by the performance of alloy 9, produced in the same manner as alloy 2, except for the decanting operation which is employed at the end of holding (i.e. the spent salt is kept on the molten alloy until before casting). In contrast to alloy 2, the best of the experimental alloys in the present work, alloy 9, does not refine the grain structure at all (Fig. 7
), in spite of very similar microstructural features (Fig. 8
) and a higher Ti content (Table 2). The loss of grain refining effect is believed to be associated with the mixing of the spent K–Al–F salts with the molten alloy as a consequence of the stirring action provided during holding by the induction furnace. The residual salt entrapped in the molten alloy is believed to have wet the boride particles, impairing their potency as nucleation sites and leading to their agglomeration at the same time [9,11]. The residual spent salt is thus claimed to be largely responsible for the variations in the performance of the grain refiner alloys.
